Sure! Here's an example where we use CSS 3D transformation to make a cube that transitions to a sphere, and changes colors as it rotates.

HTML:
```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="cube"></div>
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.container {
  perspective: 800px;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  margin: 50px auto;
}

.cube {
  position: relative;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  transform-style: preserve-3d;
  animation: spin 20s linear infinite;
}

.cube:before, .cube:after {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  background: linear-gradient(to right, #50C9C3, #96DEDA);
  transition: transform 1s ease-out;
}

.cube:before {
  transform: rotateY(90deg) translateZ(100px);
}

.cube:after {
  transform: rotateX(90deg) translateZ(100px);
}

.cube.sphere:before {
  transform: rotateX(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateX(-100px) rotateY(45deg);
}

.cube.sphere:after {
  transform: rotateY(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateY(-100px) rotateX(-45deg);
}

@keyframes spin {
  0% { transform: rotateY(0deg); }
  100% { transform: rotateY(-360deg); }
}

.cube:hover:before {
  transform: rotateX(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateX(-100px) rotateY(45deg);
}

.cube:hover:after {
  transform: rotateY(90deg) rotateZ(90deg) translateZ(100px) translateY(-100px) rotateX(-45deg);
  background: linear-gradient(to right, #FFD152, #FFE59E);
}
```

In this example, we create a container with perspective and a width and height of 200px. Inside the container, we create a cube with width and height of 100% and set `transform-style: preserve-3d` to make it a 3D object. 

We then use pseudo-elements `:before` and `:after` to create the sides of the cube, and set them to rotateY and rotateX respectively. We also use a linear gradient to make the color of the cube change from top to bottom.

When hovering over the cube, the `:before` and `:after` pseudo-elements change their transformation to make the cube transition into a sphere using `rotateX` and `rotateY`. Additionally, we change the linear gradient to create a new color theme.

Finally, we add an animation to rotate the cube 360 degrees around its Y-axis over 20s, and set it to infinite. 

Overall, this creates a visually appealing and engaging animation effect using CSS 3D transformations, transitions, and keyframes.

